1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,540
We introduce generative
experience, a paradigm where the

2
00:00:03,600 --> 00:00:06,180
interaction through which a
mental health intervention is

3
00:00:06,180 --> 00:00:10,020
enacted is not fixed in advance,
but constructed at runtime from

4
00:00:10,020 --> 00:00:12,720
the user's context and
intervention demand. We

5
00:00:12,780 --> 00:00:16,380
instantiate this paradigm in
GUIDE, a system for generative

6
00:00:16,440 --> 00:00:19,740
UI for interactive digital
experiences. Our system, GUIDE,

7
00:00:19,740 --> 00:00:24,680
has three components. First,
context elicitation. GUIDE begins

8
00:00:24,680 --> 00:00:27,200
with a short, structured
conversation to understand the

9
00:00:27,200 --> 00:00:30,620
user's situation, not just what
they're stressed about, but how

10
00:00:30,620 --> 00:00:33,740
they describe it, what feels
within their control, what their

11
00:00:33,740 --> 00:00:37,400
circumstances are right now.
This gets distilled into a

12
00:00:37,400 --> 00:00:41,740
summary that drives everything
downstream. Second, intervention

13
00:00:41,740 --> 00:00:45,460
selection. Given that context,
GUIDE generates multiple

14
00:00:45,460 --> 00:00:48,700
candidate interventions drawn
from a broad space of CBT

15
00:00:48,700 --> 00:00:51,820
informed strategies like
cognitive restructuring,

16
00:00:52,060 --> 00:00:56,320
behavioral activation, regulation
techniques. Candidates are

17
00:00:56,320 --> 00:00:59,740
evaluated by an LLM judge
against rubrics developed with

18
00:00:59,740 --> 00:01:02,760
clinical experts capturing
things like safe sequencing,

19
00:01:02,760 --> 00:01:06,960
feasibility, and specificity to
the user's situation. The

20
00:01:06,960 --> 00:01:11,280
highest scoring intervention is
selected. Third, and this is the

21
00:01:11,280 --> 00:01:15,540
new part, UX selection. Given
the selected intervention in the

22
00:01:15,540 --> 00:01:19,080
user's context, GUIDE generates
the interaction experience

23
00:01:19,080 --> 00:01:23,120
itself. It composes sequences of
modular elements, audio

24
00:01:23,120 --> 00:01:27,680
messages, timers, text inputs,
visual components. The same

25
00:01:27,680 --> 00:01:30,140
intervention can be enacted
through different structures

26
00:01:30,140 --> 00:01:33,800
depending on what the context
calls for. A second set of

27
00:01:33,800 --> 00:01:37,100
rubrics evaluates candidate
experiences for usability

28
00:01:37,340 --> 00:01:41,680
alignment with the intervention
and specificity to the user. The

29
00:01:41,680 --> 00:01:45,940
result is a combinatorial design
space, not a fixed interface.

30
00:01:46,240 --> 00:01:50,020
Every user gets a different form
of UX structure. These three

31
00:01:50,020 --> 00:01:53,020
stages mean that both what
support is offered and how it is

32
00:01:53,020 --> 00:01:56,500
experienced are generated at
runtime, tailored to each

33
00:01:56,500 --> 00:02:00,780
person's context and not fixed
in advance. Let's see GUIDE in

34
00:02:00,780 --> 00:02:03,540
action. Imagine a user is
stressed about a job interview

35
00:02:03,540 --> 00:02:08,520
tomorrow. They start by sharing
their situation by typing or by

36
00:02:08,520 --> 00:02:12,720
voice. GUIDE asks a few short,
structured questions - what's

37
00:02:12,720 --> 00:02:16,200
hardest about it? What feels
within their control, what their

38
00:02:16,200 --> 00:02:19,560
circumstances are right now?
Once the conversation is

39
00:02:19,560 --> 00:02:23,060
complete, the system distills it
into a summary the user can read

40
00:02:23,060 --> 00:02:27,440
and edit before anything else
happens. Based on this context,

41
00:02:27,440 --> 00:02:30,920
GUIDE selects an intervention
and constructs a user experience

42
00:02:31,040 --> 00:02:33,920
that can guide the user through
a stress reduction activity.

43
00:02:34,400 --> 00:02:37,220
Parts of it can contain an
encouraging audio message

44
00:02:37,220 --> 00:02:40,840
personalized to what the user
shared, followed by a prompt to

45
00:02:40,840 --> 00:02:43,780
verbalize their thoughts and
plans out loud or in writing.

46
00:02:44,620 --> 00:02:47,500
The audio reflects their
specific situation. The follow

47
00:02:47,500 --> 00:02:50,560
up prompt asks them to
articulate what they'll do next.

48
00:02:50,860 --> 00:02:53,800
But this is just one of many
possible experiences GUIDE might

49
00:02:53,800 --> 00:02:57,460
construct. The system could
instead generate a timer-based

50
00:02:57,460 --> 00:03:01,560
activity asking the user to
spend 60 seconds on a focused

51
00:03:01,560 --> 00:03:05,160
task before reflecting. Or a
short video walking them through

52
00:03:05,220 --> 00:03:08,880
a mindfulness or grounding
exercise. Or a visual card pair

53
00:03:09,120 --> 00:03:12,780
two contrasting frames helping
the user picture the shift from

54
00:03:12,780 --> 00:03:16,200
where they are now to where they
could be. Or a guided Breathing

55
00:03:16,200 --> 00:03:19,080
exercise to regulate before they
engage with the harder

56
00:03:19,080 --> 00:03:22,520
reflection work. Or a simple
text based rehearsal activity.

57
00:03:22,820 --> 00:03:26,960
Any of these experiences, any
combination, any sequence, and

58
00:03:27,020 --> 00:03:31,100
crucially, the content of each
one reflects what this specific

59
00:03:31,100 --> 00:03:34,760
person shared about their
situation. The questions use

60
00:03:34,820 --> 00:03:40,240
their words. The audio speaks to
their context. The prompts point

61
00:03:40,240 --> 00:03:44,200
to their next concrete step.
None of it is templated, the

62
00:03:44,200 --> 00:03:47,620
intervention, the modality, the
structure, all of it is

63
00:03:47,620 --> 00:03:51,640
constructed at runtime for this
person, in this moment. We

64
00:03:51,640 --> 00:03:55,000
evaluated GUIDE in a preregistered between participant

65
00:03:55,000 --> 00:03:58,300
experiment with 237
participants, comparing it

66
00:03:58,420 --> 00:04:02,100
against a strong LLM based
cognitive restructuring system.

67
00:04:02,580 --> 00:04:05,880
GUIDE produced significantly
greater stress reduction and

68
00:04:05,880 --> 00:04:09,480
better user experience. Beyond
outcomes, GUIDE generated a

69
00:04:09,480 --> 00:04:12,540
genuine diversity of
experiences, combining different

70
00:04:12,540 --> 00:04:15,660
CBT techniques and multimodal
interaction types across

71
00:04:15,660 --> 00:04:20,100
participants. No two sessions
were the same. In short, GUIDE

72
00:04:20,100 --> 00:04:23,540
is a first step toward systems
that adapt not just what support

73
00:04:23,540 --> 00:04:27,800
is offered, but how it is
experienced. Our results suggest

74
00:04:27,800 --> 00:04:31,400
this capacity can improve mental
health outcomes, and we believe

75
00:04:31,400 --> 00:04:34,460
generative experience opens a
promising direction for the

76
00:04:34,460 --> 00:04:36,740
field. Thank you for watching
this video. 

